File: SAPS members wear masks amid concerns over the spread of the COVID-19 coronavirus. JOHANNESBURG - Police Minister Bheki Cele has apologised to the Muslim community after blasphemous remarks were made during the arrest of congregants in Mpumalanga. Cele says an urgent investigation is underway to identify who made the remarks. At least 24 worshippers were taken into custody. READ: Muslim council slams police conduct Meanwhile, Cele has called on religious leaders to discourage congregants from attending gatherings during the lockdown. This after 17 people were arrested Pretoria West for violating the COVID-19 Disaster Management Lockdown Regulations. The minister says most arrests have been of people who had gathered for religious reasons since the lockdown. READ: Level four lockdown explained “This global pandemic demands that we all make huge sacrifices, making drastic adjustments to the way we live under normal circumstances. So, the sooner we accept that these are abnormal times, the closer we can all get to possible solutions towards eradicating the coronavirus once and for all,” he added. Religious gatherings have been banned to curb the spread of the coronavirus. Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.